<H2 align=3Dcenter>2. Background From Physics</H2>
<P>
<H3>Section 2.1: TORQUE</H3>
<HR>
<FONT color=3Dfirebrick>Torque </FONT>, as defined in =A9 1998 =
Merriam-Webster,=20
Incorporated<BR><BR><CITE>Main Entry: torque<BR>Function: =
noun<BR>Etymology:=20
Latin torquEre to twist<BR>1 : a force that produces or tends to produce =

rotation or torsion (an automobile engine delivers torque to the drive=20
shaft);<BR>also : a measure of the effectiveness of such a force that =
consists=20
of the product of the force and the perpendicular distance from the line =
of=20
action of the force to the axis of rotation<BR>2 : a turning or twisting =
force=20
</CITE><BR><BR>
<HR align=3Dleft width=3D"50%">
<FONT color=3Dfirebrick>Torque </FONT>, as defined in <U>University =
Physics, 8th=20
ed. 1992,</U> by Hugh D. Young:<BR><BR><CITE>The quantitative measure of =
the=20
tendency of a force to cause or change rotational motion is called =
torque.=20
</CITE>
<P></P>
<P>
<HR align=3Dleft width=3D"50%">
<FONT color=3Dfirebrick>Torque</FONT> (also called a <FONT=20
color=3Dfirebrick>moment</FONT>) is the term we use when we talk about =
forces that=20
act in a rotational manner. You apply a torque or moment when you turn a =
dial,=20
flip a lightshwitch, drill a hole or tighten a screw or bolt.<BR><BR>As =
shown in=20
the picture of a ratchet, a torque is created by a vertical force =
applied at the=20
end of the handle. The <FONT color=3Dfirebrick>force, F</FONT>, applied =
to the=20
ratchet as shown causes a tendency to rotate about point O. The force =
can be=20
broken down into two components: a <FONT color=3Dfirebrick>radial =
component,=20
F<SUB>rad</SUB></FONT>, parallel to the ratchet handle that does not =
contribute=20
to the torque, and a <FONT color=3Dfirebrick>tangential component,=20
F<SUB>tan</SUB></FONT>, perpendicular to the handle that does contribute =
to the=20
torque. The distance from point O to the point of action of F is =
described by=20
the <FONT color=3Dfirebrick>direction vector, r</FONT>. The <FONT=20
color=3Dfirebrick>moment arm, l</FONT> is the perpendicular distance =
between point=20
O and the line of action of F.<BR><BR>If we were to shorten the moment =
arm by=20
applying the force closer to the head of the ratchet,the magnitude of =
the torque=20
would decrease, even if the force remained the same. Thus, if we change =
the=20
effective length of the handle, we change the torque (see equation 1). =
